1
00:00:25,917 --> 00:00:34,183
[SPEAKER_02]: Hello, everyone, and welcome to Method Happenings, a show for and about the city of Method, and I am John Petrella.

2
00:00:34,944 --> 00:00:50,796
[SPEAKER_02]: And the purpose of this program is to give Method citizens facts and information to help you make informed choices and to discover city services or businesses you may not have been aware of.

3
00:00:51,817 --> 00:00:55,240
[SPEAKER_02]: And our guests today are Russ Kaya,

4
00:00:56,673 --> 00:00:58,077
[SPEAKER_02]: and Gus K. Office.

5
00:00:59,035 --> 00:01:03,537
[SPEAKER_02]: from the Palm Press Studio, which is located in Meffitt Square.

6
00:01:04,017 --> 00:01:05,798
[SPEAKER_02]: I hope I got the names right, guys.

7
00:01:05,878 --> 00:01:07,379
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm terrible with names.

8
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:13,042
[SPEAKER_02]: So anyhow, welcome to the show, and we're really happy to have you guys on.

9
00:01:13,322 --> 00:01:14,742
[SPEAKER_02]: It's our pleasure.

10
00:01:15,243 --> 00:01:23,246
[SPEAKER_02]: All right, we're gonna jump right in, and we'll begin by asking you both, give us a little about your background.

11
00:01:24,087 --> 00:01:24,847
[SPEAKER_02]: Who is Gus?

12
00:01:26,068 --> 00:01:26,788
[SPEAKER_02]: Who is Ross?

13
00:01:27,148 --> 00:01:28,189
[SPEAKER_01]: Sure, happy to do that.

14
00:01:29,754 --> 00:01:30,954
[SPEAKER_01]: My name is Gus Gaiffus.

15
00:01:31,074 --> 00:01:33,775
[SPEAKER_01]: I started Palm Press back in 1976.

16
00:01:34,416 --> 00:01:39,617
[SPEAKER_01]: I was the head of the photography department at Mass College of Art.

17
00:01:41,238 --> 00:01:47,400
[SPEAKER_01]: And I got excited about photography and clear description.

18
00:01:47,560 --> 00:01:54,222
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'd gone to MIT as an undergrad, so I designed and manufactured some special cameras that a lot of photographers used.

19
00:01:55,002 --> 00:02:02,669
[SPEAKER_01]: I went to graduate school at RISD in Providence, and I started a program that is terrific.

20
00:02:03,570 --> 00:02:10,076
[SPEAKER_01]: I left it in 1980 to incorporate Palm Press, which was a photographic atelier, a workshop.

21
00:02:11,137 --> 00:02:14,139
[SPEAKER_01]: And we've continued uninterrupted since then, and I've hired

22
00:02:15,140 --> 00:02:20,746
[SPEAKER_01]: almost every employee I ever had out of an internship program or out of Mass College of Art like Ross.

23
00:02:22,968 --> 00:02:27,894
[SPEAKER_01]: And I sort of look at it as continuing my education and the education of the students.

24
00:02:28,714 --> 00:02:34,360
[SPEAKER_01]: And we started off in the basement of my house in Concord and then we moved to Waltham and then we moved to

25
00:02:36,559 --> 00:02:38,601
[SPEAKER_01]: Littleton and then Pepperell.

26
00:02:38,721 --> 00:02:39,641
[SPEAKER_01]: You've been around.

27
00:02:39,881 --> 00:02:41,983
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah and each time we moved we built a darkroom.

28
00:02:42,423 --> 00:02:42,924
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

29
00:02:42,944 --> 00:02:49,648
[SPEAKER_01]: So we carried along a 14 foot tall one ton and larger that used by National Geographic.

30
00:02:50,669 --> 00:02:53,551
[SPEAKER_01]: And we've had as many as 15 employees and now we have three.

31
00:02:53,571 --> 00:02:54,372
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

32
00:02:54,612 --> 00:03:00,757
[SPEAKER_01]: And we've only been open to the public because we got seduced by the public of Medford.

33
00:03:01,537 --> 00:03:26,202
[SPEAKER_01]: well that's a good thing yeah no really is a good thing you know in the past we were in warehouses and we discovered as we were talking briefly earlier that you know Paul Revere rode up on his horse to welcome us we weren't expecting it now we look forward to it and it took us a year to build it out because we had we moved in the very beginning

34
00:03:27,182 --> 00:03:45,556
[SPEAKER_01]: of of um kovid okay and so we just stored equipment and stacks of it everywhere and finally when we couldn't find a plumber had a couple cancel on us i have this friend this chinese guy that owns four restaurants and he said i have a really good uh but you're gonna have to talk with me so i'm on the phone

35
00:03:46,397 --> 00:03:55,339
[SPEAKER_01]: The Chinese guy is, I hand him the phone, my Chinese friend explains to him from English to Chinese what to do, and we ended up with a working darkroom.

36
00:03:57,220 --> 00:03:57,680
[SPEAKER_01]: We love it.

37
00:03:58,100 --> 00:04:07,202
[SPEAKER_01]: And the iteration that we're sort of in the middle of, for me it was to wind down until I realized Ross's dream was to have this kind of a business, working with artists.

38
00:04:07,962 --> 00:04:12,583
[SPEAKER_01]: So he basically, the last year and a half, two years, has been pointing the direction we go to.

39
00:04:13,643 --> 00:04:15,664
[SPEAKER_01]: And I have to say that it's really good.

40
00:04:16,424 --> 00:04:17,225
[SPEAKER_02]: That's good to hear.

41
00:04:18,006 --> 00:04:18,807
[SPEAKER_02]: Ross, yourself?

42
00:04:18,927 --> 00:04:22,271
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, so as Gus mentioned, I went to MassArt long after he was there.

43
00:04:22,911 --> 00:04:28,918
[SPEAKER_00]: I fell in love with silver printing in the darkroom and became passionate about photographic production.

44
00:04:29,275 --> 00:04:32,238
[SPEAKER_00]: I worked at a frame shop in Brookline for a while after I graduated.

45
00:04:32,738 --> 00:04:36,261
[SPEAKER_00]: Started very part-time with Gus and slowly picked up printing jobs.

46
00:04:36,361 --> 00:04:43,868
[SPEAKER_00]: And as he mentioned, we sort of, you know, got to this point where we recognized that I wanted to continue it or, you know, transform it in a way.

47
00:04:44,228 --> 00:04:55,258
[SPEAKER_00]: And the goal for me is to sort of make it a full service production studio where we can do every part of the process from the negative or the digital file to the print, to mounting it, to framing it.

48
00:04:55,878 --> 00:05:09,400
[SPEAKER_00]: And then, yeah, as Gus mentioned, about a year ago, we built a new and used photo book store in the front of our studio, which has brought many, many people, many Medfordians in, and it's been wonderful.

49
00:05:11,562 --> 00:05:25,111
[SPEAKER_01]: It's interesting because not only do they come in to look at books and hopefully buy books, but when they see we do framing or develop film or we end up, the bottom line gets affected in an amazingly great way.

50
00:05:25,252 --> 00:05:29,915
[SPEAKER_02]: So they come in for one thing and then they find out, oh wait a minute, you do this, this, the framing.

51
00:05:30,575 --> 00:05:33,178
[SPEAKER_01]: And people will come in and spend three hours.

52
00:05:33,538 --> 00:05:35,220
[SPEAKER_01]: They'll say hello, and sometimes they don't even.

53
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:35,880
[SPEAKER_01]: They sit down.

54
00:05:36,581 --> 00:05:42,527
[SPEAKER_01]: MIT Museum donated us a really big table when they moved to their new facility and benches.

55
00:05:43,328 --> 00:05:47,011
[SPEAKER_01]: And sometimes, two, three hours later, they say thank you and goodbye.

56
00:05:47,652 --> 00:05:50,474
[SPEAKER_01]: And sometimes they buy a book, and sometimes they buy 10 books.

57
00:05:52,195 --> 00:05:55,436
[SPEAKER_01]: But we're making, you know, friends in the community.

58
00:05:55,456 --> 00:05:56,356
[SPEAKER_01]: That's great, yeah.

59
00:05:56,896 --> 00:05:59,517
[SPEAKER_01]: One of the things that Ross didn't mention, I knew he wouldn't.

60
00:06:00,797 --> 00:06:02,737
[SPEAKER_01]: He's a great bluegrass singer-songwriter.

61
00:06:02,757 --> 00:06:03,397
[SPEAKER_01]: No kidding!

62
00:06:03,437 --> 00:06:04,437
[SPEAKER_01]: He's got a hell of a band.

63
00:06:04,477 --> 00:06:05,878
[SPEAKER_01]: They just had their second CD.

64
00:06:06,258 --> 00:06:08,398
[SPEAKER_01]: He's played at Deep Cuts, at Poussin, at Notch.

65
00:06:08,418 --> 00:06:09,218
[SPEAKER_01]: Have you really?

66
00:06:09,318 --> 00:06:09,858
[SPEAKER_01]: Wow!

67
00:06:10,358 --> 00:06:10,598
[SPEAKER_02]: Nice!

68
00:06:10,618 --> 00:06:11,459
[SPEAKER_01]: They're so good.

69
00:06:11,519 --> 00:06:14,319
[SPEAKER_01]: And the music that we play in the background.

70
00:06:15,039 --> 00:06:16,820
[SPEAKER_02]: Maybe we'll bring your band here.

