00:06:16,840 --> 00:06:18,320
[SPEAKER_02]: We're looking to do a musical show.

72
00:06:18,360 --> 00:06:18,800
[SPEAKER_01]: There you go.

73
00:06:19,120 --> 00:06:33,843
[SPEAKER_02]: they're really right now they're the one of the house bands for notch no kidding so that's nice yeah it's all original i mean pretty well rounded there russ yeah yeah those are my passions anyway good that's nice nice it's nice you can do that too

74
00:06:36,265 --> 00:06:46,832
[SPEAKER_02]: So we got a pretty good idea how it started, why it started, but I guess there's so many communities around why Medford.

75
00:06:47,092 --> 00:06:50,534
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there a certain reason, is it something you heard?

76
00:06:50,554 --> 00:06:53,796
[SPEAKER_02]: I think everyone would be interested.

77
00:06:53,976 --> 00:06:54,437
[SPEAKER_01]: It was luck.

78
00:06:55,457 --> 00:07:01,382
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, we were in a warehouse in Chelsea on the second floor that was condemned.

79
00:07:01,623 --> 00:07:07,227
[SPEAKER_01]: The foundation of this 345,000 square foot warehouse was being flooded with salt water.

80
00:07:08,268 --> 00:07:12,392
[SPEAKER_01]: And slowly but surely they kicked everybody out and we were on the second floor.

81
00:07:14,633 --> 00:07:16,655
[SPEAKER_01]: And we managed to stay.

82
00:07:16,755 --> 00:07:23,121
[SPEAKER_01]: They actually offered the place as a training site for police, and they would blow down doors, they had flashbangs.

83
00:07:23,661 --> 00:07:32,188
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, it felt like a war with guns going off, and we put a big sign on the door saying, we're here, don't blow our door down.

84
00:07:33,387 --> 00:07:34,348
[SPEAKER_02]: You were in the middle of it.

85
00:07:34,409 --> 00:07:34,609
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

86
00:07:34,789 --> 00:07:36,532
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, we stayed as long as we possibly could.

87
00:07:36,772 --> 00:07:36,952
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

88
00:07:37,153 --> 00:07:37,393
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

89
00:07:37,733 --> 00:07:41,179
[SPEAKER_01]: And when we finally were looking for a place, we just lucked out.

90
00:07:41,299 --> 00:07:47,848
[SPEAKER_01]: We saw a sign on our door, on our window there, talked to the realtor.

91
00:07:49,069 --> 00:07:59,332
[SPEAKER_01]: talked to the landlord, who, you know, talked to the optician next door, and the guy that runs the Japanese restaurant that is so good.

92
00:08:00,493 --> 00:08:05,394
[SPEAKER_01]: One of my closest friends is a Japanese artist, and he said, oh, you're there?

93
00:08:05,414 --> 00:08:07,655
[SPEAKER_01]: That's the best restaurant for money in the city.

94
00:08:08,075 --> 00:08:09,855
[SPEAKER_01]: And he's a Japanese cook as well.

95
00:08:10,455 --> 00:08:12,336
[SPEAKER_02]: I know a lot of people go to that restaurant.

96
00:08:12,456 --> 00:08:15,537
[SPEAKER_01]: We started moving in and we couldn't get anything done.

97
00:08:15,937 --> 00:08:17,097
[SPEAKER_01]: We couldn't get an electrician.

98
00:08:17,617 --> 00:08:20,738
[SPEAKER_01]: We found a local guy who was scary.

99
00:08:21,058 --> 00:08:22,958
[SPEAKER_01]: Tattoos everywhere, dreads and stuff.

100
00:08:23,519 --> 00:08:26,119
[SPEAKER_01]: And he turned out to be a master carpenter.

101
00:08:26,339 --> 00:08:27,760
[SPEAKER_02]: That's the way it happens sometimes.

102
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:29,620
[SPEAKER_01]: It's amazing.

103
00:08:29,800 --> 00:08:32,541
[SPEAKER_01]: I had Ross Reed taking up a floor.

104
00:08:34,461 --> 00:08:36,962
[SPEAKER_01]: Our building at one point was a bank.

105
00:08:38,102 --> 00:08:38,483
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

106
00:08:38,703 --> 00:08:43,609
[SPEAKER_01]: And the bank that Wells Fargo that took everybody's mortgages away and made a lot of poor people.

107
00:08:43,649 --> 00:08:44,350
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I remember them.

108
00:08:45,131 --> 00:08:49,396
[SPEAKER_01]: And in the back they had a fancy women's room and stuff and we turned that into the darkroom.

109
00:08:49,416 --> 00:08:50,137
[SPEAKER_01]: Nice.

110
00:08:50,157 --> 00:08:52,259
[SPEAKER_01]: And he spent two weeks removing the old floor.

111
00:08:53,220 --> 00:08:55,302
[SPEAKER_01]: It was a lot more difficult than I thought it would be.

112
00:08:55,342 --> 00:08:57,945
[SPEAKER_02]: You guys put a major effort into this.

113
00:08:58,025 --> 00:09:04,992
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, and we had... Everybody was curious and supportive, you know.

114
00:09:05,813 --> 00:09:07,094
[SPEAKER_01]: The town was really helpful.

115
00:09:07,855 --> 00:09:11,358
[SPEAKER_01]: Our landlord was surprisingly helpful too.

116
00:09:12,279 --> 00:09:15,943
[SPEAKER_01]: He ran out of money and so the building is only half occupied and that's a pity.

117
00:09:16,603 --> 00:09:19,046
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a leaky roof ceiling and stuff.

118
00:09:20,127 --> 00:09:30,036
[SPEAKER_01]: But anyway, it turned out to be, you know, Ross had great ideas and I had, you know, been making mistakes for 50 years and learned from all of them.

119
00:09:30,777 --> 00:09:33,720
[SPEAKER_01]: So between the two of us, we made a working place.

120
00:09:35,433 --> 00:09:38,136
[SPEAKER_02]: It's good, different generations working together, I love it.

121
00:09:38,776 --> 00:09:40,978
[SPEAKER_02]: Really, it's great when you can do that.

122
00:09:41,198 --> 00:09:46,502
[SPEAKER_01]: Every once in a while, I talk about it as if it were mass art, that there's learning going on here.

123
00:09:50,425 --> 00:09:54,349
[SPEAKER_01]: It's been a great move and a wonderful shift for us to shift to a public.

124
00:09:55,209 --> 00:10:01,554
[SPEAKER_01]: Right now, there's a show at MIT, the new MIT Museum, and I worked for many years with a guy named Doc Edgerton.

125
00:10:02,373 --> 00:10:06,216
[SPEAKER_01]: He invented the high-speed photography, the milk drop, and the bullet through the apple.

126
00:10:06,817 --> 00:10:09,339
[SPEAKER_01]: And I was his teaching assistant, and I became his partner.

127
00:10:10,179 --> 00:10:17,385
[SPEAKER_01]: And when Doc died, he left a $100 million foundation to MIT, but he was collected by the Museum of Modern Art before Picasso.

128
00:10:18,025 --> 00:10:40,911
[SPEAKER_01]: Wow, so unlike most labs Yeah, where you sort of have to have terrible situation and not good ventilation and you work people too hard We always had the support of preparing exhibits So we did an exhibit for the MIT Museum nice that by the most important international publication last week said that this show produced by Palm Press

129
00:10:41,631 --> 00:10:45,672
[SPEAKER_01]: was one of the nine most important shows to see in the country.

130
00:10:45,892 --> 00:10:48,472
[SPEAKER_02]: So you guys are really, really doing some great stuff.

131
00:10:48,712 --> 00:10:49,152
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, we are.

132
00:10:49,192 --> 00:10:49,753
[SPEAKER_00]: We're proud of it.

133
00:10:49,933 --> 00:10:50,513
[SPEAKER_02]: And that's great.

134
00:10:50,573 --> 00:10:51,673
[SPEAKER_02]: And you should be proud of it.

135
00:10:51,713 --> 00:10:51,973
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

136
00:10:52,253 --> 00:10:54,613
[SPEAKER_00]: And we're happy to work with, you know, with museums like that.

137
00:10:54,633 --> 00:11:00,955
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we're also happy to work with individual artists and then also just individuals who, you know, need things printed and stuff like that.

138
00:11:01,375 --> 00:11:03,195
[SPEAKER_01]: Somebody came in with a framing job.

139
00:11:04,155 --> 00:11:06,316
[SPEAKER_01]: Ross had on Ross's day off.

140
00:11:06,816 --> 00:11:07,496
[SPEAKER_01]: And it turns out,

141
00:11:07,976 --> 00:11:12,161
[SPEAKER_01]: It was the guy that influenced him to become a musician when he was in high school.

142
00:11:12,181 --> 00:11:13,602
[SPEAKER_01]: That's right, yeah.

143
00:11:13,622 --> 00:11:14,543
[SPEAKER_01]: Small world.

144
00:11:14,583 --> 00:11:15,805
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, you work with a hero.

145
00:11:20,590 --> 00:11:29,300
[SPEAKER_02]: Apparently, Gus, I'm going to direct this question to you, you're well connected.

146
00:11:30,298 --> 00:11:30,938
[SPEAKER_02]: to the arts.

147
00:11:31,899 --> 00:11:39,901
[SPEAKER_02]: And I'm told that, you know, by people giving you a prior role, I guess you sat on the board of directors for the... DeCordova.

148
00:11:39,921 --> 00:11:40,702
[SPEAKER_01]: DeCordova Museum.

149
00:11:40,722 --> 00:11:41,222
[SPEAKER_01]: For 22 years.

150
00:11:41,442 --> 00:11:43,303
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you, yeah, I mean that was something.

151
00:11:43,603 --> 00:11:53,006
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean... Well, you know, most of the, we, we were, we lived in Concord where we were fortunate to raise our two boys and we bought probably the last $43,000 house in Concord.

152
00:11:55,547 --> 00:11:57,748
[SPEAKER_02]: Wow, that was a while ago.

153
00:11:59,148 --> 00:11:57,748
75.

154
00:12:00,168 --> 00:12:07,590
[SPEAKER_01]: And I had this friend, I mean we love museums, we're deeply involved, we've donated work all over, we've published 65 portfolios.

155
00:12:09,250 --> 00:12:17,812
[SPEAKER_01]: One of the shows that we did that came out of that was at the Museum of Fine Arts, a rock and roll show of the Grateful Dead and the Jefferson Airplane, portfolios we did.

156
00:12:19,312 --> 00:12:24,033
[SPEAKER_01]: But the director of the Decordova, who became a dear friend, he and his wife, me and my wife,

157
00:12:24,734 --> 00:12:25,895
[SPEAKER_01]: Said I'd like you on the board.

158
00:12:26,015 --> 00:12:30,321
[SPEAKER_01]: I said, you know board members give $50,000 or more a year.

159
00:12:30,421 --> 00:12:31,643
[SPEAKER_01]: I can't do that, right?

160
00:12:31,803 --> 00:12:38,472
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm an assistant professor in an art school And he laughed and he said you don't have to he said your presence will

161
00:12:39,653 --> 00:12:46,737
[SPEAKER_01]: And then I realized that I'd published a lot of very important portfolios, and many of them had become valuable.

162
00:12:48,238 --> 00:12:51,940
[SPEAKER_01]: And so I would donate one of my artist's proofs.

163
00:12:52,320 --> 00:12:56,082
[SPEAKER_01]: So Arlette and I ended up the largest donors to that museum.

164
