00:14:04,138 --> 00:14:04,758
[SPEAKER_01]: It was so good.

187
00:14:05,819 --> 00:14:13,381
[SPEAKER_01]: But yeah, Doc was a big sort of lift into it because I ended up representing the estate.

188
00:14:13,481 --> 00:14:19,863
[SPEAKER_01]: So we had, you know, we would sell photographs that I would produce that Doc and I would share the proceeds.

189
00:14:20,363 --> 00:14:26,384
[SPEAKER_01]: But it allowed us to make sure that when we built our place out, it was the very best of it.

190
00:14:26,445 --> 00:14:27,645
[SPEAKER_01]: We have great equipment.

191
00:14:28,025 --> 00:14:28,285
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

192
00:14:28,365 --> 00:14:29,405
[SPEAKER_01]: I can imagine.

193
00:14:29,545 --> 00:14:30,746
[SPEAKER_01]: It's really good equipment.

194
00:14:30,766 --> 00:14:30,946
[SPEAKER_01]: Nice.

195
00:14:31,166 --> 00:14:31,366
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

196
00:14:31,906 --> 00:14:33,848
[SPEAKER_01]: And we did the New York Times Photo Archives.

197
00:14:34,028 --> 00:14:36,289
[SPEAKER_01]: We did National Geographic Centennial Exhibit.

198
00:14:36,750 --> 00:14:38,711
[SPEAKER_01]: So we ended up working for major clients.

199
00:14:38,751 --> 00:14:39,592
[SPEAKER_02]: You certainly have.

200
00:14:39,872 --> 00:14:40,953
[SPEAKER_02]: National Geographic.

201
00:14:41,113 --> 00:14:41,753
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, that was fun.

202
00:14:41,893 --> 00:14:43,334
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, I can only imagine.

203
00:14:44,855 --> 00:14:46,036
[SPEAKER_02]: National Geographic.

204
00:14:46,717 --> 00:14:48,918
[SPEAKER_02]: That's a feather in the cap, as they say.

205
00:14:48,938 --> 00:14:50,539
[SPEAKER_02]: It certainly is.

206
00:14:52,640 --> 00:14:59,142
[SPEAKER_02]: All right, so we know you guys do much, much more than just photography, okay?

207
00:15:00,283 --> 00:15:02,643
[SPEAKER_02]: You have a darkroom, okay?

208
00:15:05,184 --> 00:15:10,206
[SPEAKER_02]: For photo development, and you also offer framing services.

209
00:15:11,125 --> 00:15:18,569
[SPEAKER_01]: And we also have a digital lab, the modern technology that's not wet and not chemistry.

210
00:15:19,469 --> 00:15:25,032
[SPEAKER_01]: For color, it's probably better than any process that's typically available now.

211
00:15:29,985 --> 00:15:34,367
[SPEAKER_02]: This is new, the process, or is it an old process?

212
00:15:34,607 --> 00:15:38,929
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm trying to... 30 years, 20, 30 years, but it's gotten a whole lot better in the last 10 years.

213
00:15:38,949 --> 00:15:40,110
[SPEAKER_02]: It has, so there's a lot of improvements.

214
00:15:40,130 --> 00:15:43,031
[SPEAKER_01]: And Ross is an expert at the color corrections and stuff that you make.

215
00:15:43,572 --> 00:15:52,076
[SPEAKER_01]: So people will come and say, you know, I got this problem, and when they're done, we almost always have people say, I never thought it could be that good.

216
00:15:53,096 --> 00:15:56,017
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, the band words at Palm Press are that's good enough.

217
00:15:56,157 --> 00:16:01,739
[SPEAKER_01]: So sometimes we find ourselves with really small projects spending more money than we're making.

218
00:16:01,999 --> 00:16:03,480
[SPEAKER_01]: But it's a beautiful thing that we do.

219
00:16:03,560 --> 00:16:05,681
[SPEAKER_01]: And there are big projects that make up for all of that.

220
00:16:07,061 --> 00:16:09,642
[SPEAKER_02]: The framing, I mean, I'm just curious now.

221
00:16:10,663 --> 00:16:11,043
[SPEAKER_02]: Anything?

222
00:16:11,063 --> 00:16:19,286
[SPEAKER_02]: I can walk in, you spoke earlier, I can walk in with a sports jersey that's autographed, I want to frame, you guys will do it.

223
00:16:19,366 --> 00:16:20,046
[SPEAKER_00]: Just about anything.

224
00:16:20,226 --> 00:16:21,267
[SPEAKER_00]: Artwork, anything.

225
00:16:22,047 --> 00:16:25,969
[SPEAKER_00]: One thing I love about framing is there are endless solutions to anything.

226
00:16:26,009 --> 00:16:30,830
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, there's always going to be an inexpensive solution and for a lot of people, that's what you're looking for.

227
00:16:31,290 --> 00:16:39,894
[SPEAKER_00]: And then it just can go anywhere from there, you know, complex solutions with various mounting and like jerseys where maybe you're going to be pinning it to something.

228
00:16:40,434 --> 00:16:43,715
[SPEAKER_00]: But framing is just an endless creative solution.

229
00:16:44,899 --> 00:16:45,520
[SPEAKER_01]: It is, yeah.

230
00:16:45,961 --> 00:16:50,428
[SPEAKER_01]: So Ross, when he worked at the frame shop while he was going to college, he had two jobs.

231
00:16:50,468 --> 00:16:51,610
[SPEAKER_01]: He was also a barista.

232
00:16:53,565 --> 00:16:54,365
[SPEAKER_01]: You've been around.

233
00:16:54,445 --> 00:16:54,665
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

234
00:16:55,286 --> 00:16:56,106
[SPEAKER_01]: Gotta make money somehow.

235
00:16:56,146 --> 00:16:57,646
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, we all do.

236
00:16:57,666 --> 00:16:59,807
[SPEAKER_01]: He upped our coffee level completely.

237
00:17:00,167 --> 00:17:00,507
[SPEAKER_01]: Good.

238
00:17:00,827 --> 00:17:03,288
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll actually do a shout out to Locolito.

239
00:17:03,848 --> 00:17:04,248
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

240
00:17:04,328 --> 00:17:08,590
[SPEAKER_01]: Which is a coffee shop that opened a few months ago a block and a half away from us.

241
00:17:08,750 --> 00:17:09,810
[SPEAKER_02]: Now I've heard of them.

242
00:17:10,010 --> 00:17:13,831
[SPEAKER_01]: We haven't had them on the show, but maybe that's another show up the road.

243
00:17:13,911 --> 00:17:16,192
[SPEAKER_01]: They do Tenoch and Tacubana.

244
00:17:17,293 --> 00:17:19,675
[SPEAKER_01]: It's the same brothers, they do it all.

245
00:17:19,695 --> 00:17:20,295
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, is it real?

246
00:17:20,335 --> 00:17:21,056
[SPEAKER_02]: I didn't know that.

247
00:17:21,416 --> 00:17:22,277
[SPEAKER_02]: I had no idea.

248
00:17:22,297 --> 00:17:23,498
[SPEAKER_02]: Same people.

249
00:17:23,819 --> 00:17:24,800
[SPEAKER_02]: I go to the restaurant.

250
00:17:25,140 --> 00:17:32,247
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, making coffee isn't a whole lot different than making the chemicals that we use in the darkroom.

251
00:17:33,848 --> 00:17:38,492
[SPEAKER_01]: Fortunately, you know, the chemical, not doing color photography

252
00:17:39,273 --> 00:17:44,536
[SPEAKER_01]: doing that with inkjet printers, we don't generate bad chemistry.

253
00:17:45,236 --> 00:17:54,121
[SPEAKER_01]: I had a huge color lab in Pepperell, and we had to have reprocessors for everything that went into the water system to make sure that we weren't contaminating it all.

254
00:17:54,141 --> 00:17:55,782
[SPEAKER_02]: That's right, back in the day, yeah.

255
00:17:55,962 --> 00:17:57,003
[SPEAKER_02]: A lot of that went on.

256
00:17:59,144 --> 00:18:02,286
[SPEAKER_02]: So I mean, we talked about all the other things you provide.

257
00:18:03,567 --> 00:18:04,867
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you also do classes?

258
00:18:06,223 --> 00:18:08,985
[SPEAKER_00]: So there are sort of two sides to that.

259
00:18:10,286 --> 00:18:17,211
[SPEAKER_00]: We do artist talks with artists that we like, mostly that have produced, published photography books.

260
00:18:17,951 --> 00:18:21,974
[SPEAKER_00]: And we'll do a Q&A with a book signing and we'll have them talk about their process.

261
00:18:22,014 --> 00:18:29,119
[SPEAKER_00]: And a lot of the guests are other photographers who are interested in publishing their own book or interested in how it was made.

262
00:18:30,040 --> 00:18:30,980
[SPEAKER_00]: And those are really wonderful.

263
00:18:31,020 --> 00:18:33,601
[SPEAKER_00]: We frequently do them on Thursday nights, about once a month.

264
00:18:34,201 --> 00:18:39,902
[SPEAKER_00]: And then the other side of it is we've started doing one-on-one lessons in the darkroom.

265
00:18:40,583 --> 00:18:47,824
[SPEAKER_00]: I work directly with somebody who maybe has printed a little bit in the darkroom or maybe never has, but they're interested in it.

266
00:18:48,544 --> 00:18:54,746
[SPEAKER_00]: And I sort of work with them to make a really beautiful print of one of their photographs.

267
00:18:55,246 --> 00:18:58,987
[SPEAKER_00]: And I show them how to make certain decisions about how to make it look the way you want.

268
00:18:59,427 --> 00:19:08,910
[SPEAKER_00]: whether it's altering the contrast or adding or subtracting time to your exposure, and then, you know, how to process it properly so that it's going to be archival.

269
00:19:09,190 --> 00:19:12,051
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's been very satisfying for me and I think for the people who have done it.

270
00:19:12,211 --> 00:19:12,811
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm sure it is.

271
00:19:12,851 --> 00:19:14,532
[SPEAKER_02]: So you actually do one-on-one.

272
00:19:14,572 --> 00:19:18,293
[SPEAKER_02]: So someone could call, set it up with you, and boom.

273
00:19:18,513 --> 00:19:19,933
[SPEAKER_02]: It's really interesting.

274
00:19:19,953 --> 00:19:21,334
[SPEAKER_02]: It's actually work in a darkroom.

275
00:19:21,735 --> 00:19:27,762
[SPEAKER_01]: and we gain friends of the darkroom and friends of the community and we've actually had a marriage come about because of that.

276
00:19:27,782 --> 00:19:28,903
[SPEAKER_01]: Well there you go!

277
00:19:29,103 --> 00:19:29,744
[SPEAKER_01]: Wow!

278
00:19:30,965 --> 00:19:38,794
[SPEAKER_01]: But no, it's really, it's, I remember I started when I was nine years old and it was my dad's hobby and once a week we turned the bathroom into a darkroom.

279
00:19:39,395 --> 00:19:39,855
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

280
00:19:39,996 --> 00:19:41,517
[SPEAKER_01]: The Jean Dark he called it.

281
00:19:41,537 --> 00:19:42,218
[SPEAKER_02]: That had to be a...

282
00:19:43,159 --> 00:19:44,560
[SPEAKER_01]: It had to be quite a dark room.

283
00:19:45,140 --> 00:19:47,042
[SPEAKER_01]: It was, you know, plywood on the toilet.

284
00:19:48,363 --> 00:19:57,909
[SPEAKER_01]: But it worked, you know, and fortunately the houses we had were always one and a half bathrooms, so no emergencies messed up what we were doing.

285
00:19:57,929 --> 00:19:58,690
[SPEAKER_01]: I would hope not, yeah.

286
00:19:58,710 --> 00:19:59,631
[SPEAKER_01]: But it was like magic.

287
00:19:59,731 --> 00:20:06,836
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, you put this piece of paper after you expose it to what was like a slide projector, and all of a sudden it came up.

288
00:20:07,476 --> 00:20:10,638
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's still like, it's still really exciting.

289
00:20:11,278 --> 00:20:29,247
[SPEAKER_01]: And so to introduce people to it, particularly when they've gone from digital, where it's just, you know, a bigger version of your printer, to actually seeing, and Ross sort of, you know, the changes that you can make with your hands and with, are so subtle, and it's kind of like, you know, tuning a guitar.

290
00:20:29,648 --> 00:20:31,148
[SPEAKER_01]: At one point, it's beautiful.

291
00:20:31,829 --> 00:20:33,230
[SPEAKER_01]: Before it, it's cacophonous.

292
00:20:34,500 --> 00:20:40,203
[SPEAKER_00]: And then to add to that, we do offer daily rentals for our darkroom as well.

293
00:20:40,244 --> 00:20:42,725
[SPEAKER_00]: We're not in the darkroom every day like Gus mentioned earlier.

294
00:20:43,085 --> 00:20:45,867
[SPEAKER_00]: So people who might do a one-on-one session with me, if they

295
00:20:46,287 --> 00:20:50,331
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, start to get the hang of it and they want to do more of it themselves, they can rent the darkroom for a day.

296
00:20:50,491 --> 00:20:53,113
[SPEAKER_02]: So obviously they have to know what they're doing before they rent the darkroom.

297
00:20:53,133 --> 00:20:54,514
[SPEAKER_00]: And they get vetted by Ross.

298
00:20:54,534 --> 00:20:55,856
[SPEAKER_02]: I would hope so, yeah.

299
00:20:56,036 --> 00:20:57,757
[SPEAKER_01]: If somebody says, well, I know what to do.

300
00:20:59,118 --> 00:21:05,224
[SPEAKER_01]: One of the enlargers we have, when I bought it new many years ago, it was $25,000 and they don't make it anymore.

301
00:21:05,344 --> 00:21:06,265
[SPEAKER_02]: Right, so there you go.

302
00:21:06,285 --> 00:21:08,427
[SPEAKER_01]: So you don't want somebody messing that up.

303
00:21:08,467 --> 00:21:09,788
[SPEAKER_02]: No, that's what I figured, yeah.

304
00:21:10,268 --> 00:21:11,129
[SPEAKER_02]: Absolutely nice.

305
00:21:12,672 --> 00:21:21,278
[SPEAKER_02]: So, you know, given the advancements in technology, you know, how tough is it?

306
00:21:22,019 --> 00:21:29,585
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, you're off of photography in the age of digital photos, I mean.

307
00:21:32,935 --> 00:21:34,256
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't even know how to ask the question.

308
00:21:34,276 --> 00:21:40,340
[SPEAKER_01]: Well it's pretty easy to make a print that looks a lot like what you want it to, digitally.

309
00:21:41,720 --> 00:21:48,285
[SPEAKER_01]: It may not have the richness of a fine art print made on gelatin silver paper.

310
00:21:49,185 --> 00:21:51,026
[SPEAKER_01]: But you may not even give a damn about that.

311
00:21:51,126 --> 00:21:55,627
[SPEAKER_01]: You may just want to see your great aunt, you know, looking good.

312
00:21:57,228 --> 00:22:02,609
[SPEAKER_01]: But at some point you become, you know, I have a friend that always hated baseball.

313
00:22:03,449 --> 00:22:08,091
[SPEAKER_01]: And when high def TV came, he could all of a sudden see the spin on the ball from the pitcher.

314
00:22:08,711 --> 00:22:10,572
[SPEAKER_01]: And it changed it for him completely.

315
00:22:10,932 --> 00:22:14,413
[SPEAKER_01]: And so when you tune people into the subtleties of what's possible,

316
00:22:15,273 --> 00:22:22,200
[SPEAKER_01]: all of a sudden they become, it's like listening to your favorite song on an AM radio and then on a good stereo system.

317
00:22:22,981 --> 00:22:25,984
[SPEAKER_01]: Some people don't care, some people go, whoa.

318
00:22:27,005 --> 00:22:28,947
[SPEAKER_01]: We want the people to go, whoa.

319
00:22:29,608 --> 00:22:30,829
[SPEAKER_01]: We've helped set up dark rooms.

320
00:22:32,070 --> 00:22:33,752
[SPEAKER_01]: People are always reaching out to me.

321
00:22:34,276 --> 00:22:40,303
[SPEAKER_01]: My dad had a darkroom, it's in the basement, we don't know what to do with it, and we have a list of schools that we have them donated to.

322
00:22:41,365 --> 00:22:44,108
[SPEAKER_01]: They're usually not worth the kind of money they cost way back when.

323
00:22:45,450 --> 00:22:48,514
[SPEAKER_01]: But it's better to pass them on than throw them in the junkyard.

324
00:22:49,590 --> 00:22:53,093
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there a lot of things involved with these old dock rooms?

325
00:22:53,393 --> 00:22:54,434
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm just curious.

326
00:22:54,815 --> 00:22:56,576
[SPEAKER_00]: A lot of equipment, a lot of maintenance.

327
00:22:57,857 --> 00:23:01,881
[SPEAKER_00]: We have a graveyard of spare parts for when things go wrong with ours.

328
00:23:01,961 --> 00:23:04,102
[SPEAKER_01]: That's what I was going to ask.

329
00:23:04,803 --> 00:23:08,506
[SPEAKER_01]: Camera repairmen used to cost $50 to get your camera tuned up.

330
00:23:08,626 --> 00:23:09,167
[SPEAKER_01]: Now it's $350.

331
00:23:09,247 --> 00:23:12,550
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's more than some cameras cost.

332
00:23:13,931 --> 00:23:16,853
[SPEAKER_01]: You should come by sometime and we'll put you in the dark room with us.

333
00:23:16,893 --> 00:23:18,154
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, I'm gonna come by.

334
00:23:18,234 --> 00:23:19,455
[SPEAKER_01]: It's absolute magic.

335
00:23:19,595 --> 00:23:20,375
[SPEAKER_01]: It's so cool.

336
00:23:20,755 --> 00:23:24,678
[SPEAKER_02]: I actually found some ancient stuff from 30 years ago and I gave it to her.

337
00:23:24,698 --> 00:23:25,499
[SPEAKER_02]: We're gonna process it.

338
00:23:25,559 --> 00:23:26,400
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I gave it to her.

339
00:23:26,440 --> 00:23:27,360
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know what's on it.

340
00:23:27,400 --> 00:23:28,221
[SPEAKER_02]: I have no idea.

341
00:23:28,261 --> 00:23:30,883
[SPEAKER_02]: I hope it doesn't get me in any trouble.

342
00:23:30,903 --> 00:23:32,624
[SPEAKER_02]: You never know.

343
00:23:32,704 --> 00:23:37,287
[SPEAKER_01]: Years ago, before I went off to college, I worked at a camera store in Washington, D.C.

344
00:23:38,208 --> 00:23:40,209
[SPEAKER_01]: and we had this elderly woman come in.

345
00:23:41,210 --> 00:23:47,634
[SPEAKER_01]: And she had a roll of film that she discovered from 616 film, from a camera that hadn't been made for 50 years.

346
00:23:48,615 --> 00:23:51,117
[SPEAKER_01]: And she said, I don't know if it's any good.

347
00:23:51,137 --> 00:23:53,759
[SPEAKER_01]: And I said, well, it's a dollar to process the film.

348
00:23:54,279 --> 00:24:00,643
[SPEAKER_01]: And she clearly was well-dressed and wealthy, and she lived in a house in downtown Washington, DC.

349
00:24:01,124 --> 00:24:02,645
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't want to waste the money.

350
00:24:02,985 --> 00:24:05,927
[SPEAKER_01]: And I said, well, you know, I'll throw it in when I develop my own film.

351
00:24:06,307 --> 00:24:07,388
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't want to accept charity.

352
00:24:07,928 --> 00:24:10,989
[SPEAKER_01]: So she came in once a day for two weeks asking.

353
00:24:11,449 --> 00:24:13,169
[SPEAKER_01]: And finally I said, well, where did you store it?

354
00:24:13,769 --> 00:24:14,850
[SPEAKER_01]: And she said, in the attic.

355
00:24:15,790 --> 00:24:17,250
[SPEAKER_01]: I said, is the attic air conditioned?

356
00:24:17,350 --> 00:24:18,050
[SPEAKER_01]: She said, no.

357
00:24:18,130 --> 00:24:19,811
[SPEAKER_01]: So attic in Washington, D.C.

358
00:24:19,831 --> 00:24:22,751
[SPEAKER_01]: in the summer is 140 degrees and it's cooked.

359
00:24:22,851 --> 00:24:25,692
[SPEAKER_01]: So finally I said, you know, I can make sure.

360
00:24:25,712 --> 00:24:27,573
[SPEAKER_01]: And she said, how would you do that?

361
00:24:27,613 --> 00:24:28,593
[SPEAKER_01]: I said, let me look at the film.

362
00:24:28,633 --> 00:24:29,393
[SPEAKER_01]: And I opened up the film.

363
00:24:30,807 --> 00:24:32,067
[SPEAKER_01]: And I said, nothing on it.

364
00:24:32,228 --> 00:24:32,828
[SPEAKER_01]: It's no good.

365
00:24:33,208 --> 00:24:34,488
[SPEAKER_01]: She thanked me so much.

366
00:24:34,968 --> 00:24:35,888
[SPEAKER_01]: She could sleep better.

367
00:24:36,068 --> 00:24:37,649
[SPEAKER_01]: And we threw the film away for her.

368
00:24:38,409 --> 00:24:42,530
[SPEAKER_01]: But, you know, there's the process is weird.

369
00:24:42,930 --> 00:24:44,010
[SPEAKER_01]: It's magic.

370
00:24:45,071 --> 00:24:49,452
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, I have similar those what I gave him is a roll of film.

371
00:24:49,492 --> 00:24:50,012
[SPEAKER_02]: It's been in the

372
00:24:52,122 --> 00:24:55,225
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm pretty sure it's you, because it's been in the container for 30 years now.

373
00:24:56,166 --> 00:24:58,868
[SPEAKER_02]: Fortunately, it was never in an attic or, you know.

374
00:24:58,888 --> 00:25:03,772
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, when we print it for National, that's a centennial exhibit for National Geographic.

375
00:25:04,272 --> 00:25:06,294
[SPEAKER_01]: And the next time you come by, I'll show you the book we did.

376
00:25:06,414 --> 00:25:07,935
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, I'm definitely going to.

377
00:25:08,236 --> 00:25:10,597
[SPEAKER_02]: Once he gives me a call, tells me I'm all set, I'll be in.

378
00:25:11,359 --> 00:25:17,041
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, they had film with negatives that were 100 years old that were anonymous that we made prints from.

379
00:25:18,442 --> 00:25:25,445
[SPEAKER_01]: Part of the problem is that there was a period of time in the 30s when they made film using acetate and nitrate.

380
00:25:25,705 --> 00:25:29,306
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's why there's no Hollywood films from the silent era, because they self-immolated.

381
00:25:29,346 --> 00:25:30,187
[SPEAKER_01]: They would explode.

382
00:25:30,307 --> 00:25:32,127
[SPEAKER_02]: Right, I remember that, the acetate.

383
00:25:32,147 --> 00:25:33,068
[SPEAKER_01]: So, Geographic.

384
00:25:33,908 --> 00:25:44,331
[SPEAKER_01]: Actually, the New York Times in 1946 threw away one and a half million negatives of prints that they had published in the previous 50 years of the Times.

385
00:25:45,151 --> 00:25:51,472
[SPEAKER_01]: And if the photography editor knew you, you know, hey Joe Blow, we got 20 contact sheets of your film.

386
00:25:51,492 --> 00:25:52,753
[SPEAKER_01]: Do you want it or should we toss it?

387
00:25:53,193 --> 00:25:54,133
[SPEAKER_01]: Most of them said toss it.

388
00:25:55,484 --> 00:26:05,041
[SPEAKER_01]: And so when we ended up working for the National Geographic, we ended up making copy negatives, really high quality, very expensive, so we could reproduce those images.

389
00:26:06,556 --> 00:26:09,517
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, it's funny, I have, I think they called it Kodachrome.

390
00:26:09,857 --> 00:26:11,157
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, that was the best color.

391
00:26:11,917 --> 00:26:13,858
[SPEAKER_02]: Still in the box, never been used.

392
00:26:14,258 --> 00:26:15,818
[SPEAKER_02]: I have a few of them.

393
00:26:15,838 --> 00:26:28,881
[SPEAKER_02]: My father was big into, you know, taking pictures, photography, whatever, and I ended up with a bunch of, I don't even know where it came from, but it's all unused, original box, it's never opened.

394
00:26:29,001 --> 00:26:31,362
[SPEAKER_01]: That's wonderful, but you can't process Kodachrome anymore.

395
00:26:31,442 --> 00:26:31,882
[SPEAKER_01]: No more.

396
00:26:32,502 --> 00:26:33,963
[SPEAKER_01]: It was a chemical process.

397
00:26:34,083 --> 00:26:34,883
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I figured.

398
00:26:36,143 --> 00:26:40,885
[SPEAKER_01]: It read the chemistry and it changed it each time and there was two labs in the world that did it.

399
00:26:41,786 --> 00:26:44,687
[SPEAKER_01]: And Kodak shot them both down.

400
00:26:45,248 --> 00:26:51,131
[SPEAKER_02]: My wife's going to be afraid now because she's going to hear what you said and she's going to think there's something on there that's going to explode in my car or something.

401
00:26:51,171 --> 00:26:54,372
[SPEAKER_01]: No, that has to be a film that was made in the early 30s.

402
00:26:54,532 --> 00:26:55,373
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, well that's good.

403
00:26:55,553 --> 00:26:57,794
[SPEAKER_01]: I hope this isn't the early 30s.

404
00:26:57,874 --> 00:27:00,395
[SPEAKER_01]: You can tell when it goes bad because it smells like vinegar.

405
00:27:00,435 --> 00:27:01,756
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know, it's hard.

406
00:27:04,497 --> 00:27:07,059
[SPEAKER_02]: Maybe when I come pick up the other stuff, I'll show you this.

407
00:27:07,099 --> 00:27:08,080
[SPEAKER_02]: You can take a look at it.

408
00:27:08,100 --> 00:27:09,001
[SPEAKER_02]: There's quite a bit of it.

409
00:27:09,041 --> 00:27:13,124
[SPEAKER_01]: There are people that collect old film rolls, but in the boxes.

410
00:27:13,164 --> 00:27:14,685
[SPEAKER_01]: They don't want them opened up.

411
00:27:14,725 --> 00:27:15,946
[SPEAKER_01]: These are all sealed, yeah.

412
00:27:16,066 --> 00:27:17,547
[SPEAKER_02]: That's great.

413
00:27:17,767 --> 00:27:18,408
[SPEAKER_02]: When I come by.

414
00:27:18,428 --> 00:27:21,750
[SPEAKER_02]: All right, so now we've got to get back to the show.

415
00:27:22,351 --> 00:27:24,632
[SPEAKER_02]: I could talk to you guys for, oh boy, can you go on and on.

416
00:27:24,652 --> 00:27:27,034
[SPEAKER_02]: You must tell we can talk to you.

417
00:27:27,194 --> 00:27:30,377
[SPEAKER_02]: All right, so you spoke about you're also a bookstore.

418
00:27:31,957 --> 00:27:35,098
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you tell us a little bit more types of books you sell?

419
00:27:36,338 --> 00:27:39,359
[SPEAKER_02]: Ross would know that best because he edits in prices.

420
00:27:39,779 --> 00:27:41,660
[SPEAKER_02]: And you sell used books too, correct?

421
00:27:41,960 --> 00:27:42,360
[SPEAKER_02]: Mostly.

422
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:45,041
[SPEAKER_02]: And is there a certain criteria?

423
00:27:45,461 --> 00:27:49,002
[SPEAKER_02]: What do you use or how do you go about getting these books?

424
00:27:49,282 --> 00:27:52,864
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, many of them are used books that have come from Gus's collection.

425
00:27:53,864 --> 00:28:02,949
[SPEAKER_00]: He's been an avid collector for probably 50 years and hilariously bought 2, 3, 4, 5 copies of everything.

426
00:28:02,969 --> 00:28:07,531
[SPEAKER_00]: So we've been carting around books in boxes for years.

427
00:28:07,912 --> 00:28:10,173
[SPEAKER_01]: We've given many non-photo books to the library.

428
00:28:10,533 --> 00:28:24,033
[SPEAKER_02]: that's nice what a great library you have oh yes oh man can't say enough good about it yep yep and they did a tremendous job with that library it's it's i don't even call it a library it's a community it is center it's uh they have everything yeah

429
00:28:24,412 --> 00:28:32,717
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, eventually after I recognized how many duplicate books there were, I convinced Gus that we could probably get rid of some, save some space, make a few bucks.

430
00:28:33,558 --> 00:28:39,261
[SPEAKER_00]: And in doing so, he and I have both collected books from newer photo book publishers.

431
00:28:40,001 --> 00:28:42,683
[SPEAKER_00]: And they've become increasingly expensive.

432
00:28:43,243 --> 00:28:45,204
[SPEAKER_00]: Maybe 10 years ago, you could get a good book for $40, $45.

433
00:28:45,265 --> 00:28:46,405
[SPEAKER_00]: And now a good book is $65, $70, even $75.

434
00:28:52,509 --> 00:28:55,611
[SPEAKER_00]: We'd collect them and occasionally we'd get one that was really, really beautiful.

435
00:28:56,612 --> 00:29:01,435
[SPEAKER_00]: But a lot of the time you'd get it and you might be a little underwhelmed by it and wish you didn't spend the 70 bucks on it.

436
00:29:02,936 --> 00:29:04,617
[SPEAKER_00]: When I was in school, I was obsessed with it.

437
00:29:04,658 --> 00:29:07,600
[SPEAKER_00]: I was going to the Mass Art Library all the time and looking at all the books.

438
00:29:07,640 --> 00:29:10,842
[SPEAKER_00]: It was the way to see large bodies of photographs.

439
00:29:11,977 --> 00:29:15,880
[SPEAKER_00]: When I got out of school, I had to buy them all and I can't really afford that.

440
00:29:16,501 --> 00:29:21,785
[SPEAKER_00]: I wish that there was somewhere that I could go to just look at them and decide, this one's worth the 70 bucks.

441
00:29:21,805 --> 00:29:22,546
[SPEAKER_00]: I want to keep that.

442
00:29:22,926 --> 00:29:29,151
[SPEAKER_00]: So we wanted to offer a place where people could come and look at them and decide if it's worth what it costs.

443
00:29:30,392 --> 00:29:31,513
[SPEAKER_00]: Or just come and look at them.

444
00:29:31,933 --> 00:29:36,277
[SPEAKER_00]: If somebody comes and doesn't buy one, we're happy to have them to just look at.

445
00:29:36,597 --> 00:29:43,704
[SPEAKER_01]: It was a shared experience from us too because occasionally we get a book and we say, it's not as good as...

446
00:29:45,445 --> 00:29:50,487
[SPEAKER_01]: our opinions, our sensibilities from music to photographers resonates.

447
00:29:50,567 --> 00:29:55,349
[SPEAKER_01]: It's really, we don't have a lot of arguments about what I think is great and he thinks is crap.

448
00:29:56,849 --> 00:30:03,031
[SPEAKER_01]: But what would happen is if you'd get indications of 10 new books and you could afford two.

449
00:30:03,992 --> 00:30:05,632
[SPEAKER_01]: And you say, well, next month I'll do it.

450
00:30:05,772 --> 00:30:08,593
[SPEAKER_01]: And they would sell out and they'd be $250.

451
00:30:09,434 --> 00:30:12,455
[SPEAKER_01]: So we now carry five or six book publishers

452
00:30:13,255 --> 00:30:20,078
[SPEAKER_01]: we select the best from and so we have a wall of all new books and those are the ones where we have book signings usually and those are exciting.

453
00:30:20,198 --> 00:30:25,160
[SPEAKER_01]: We did them on Saturdays and nobody came because if it was a nice Saturday who wanted to go to town.

454
00:30:25,680 --> 00:30:28,321
[SPEAKER_01]: We did them on Thursday nights and we had some that were standing room only.

455
00:30:28,481 --> 00:30:31,143
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, what a difference just picking the right day.

456
00:30:31,203 --> 00:30:32,183
[SPEAKER_01]: It's amazing.

457
00:30:32,483 --> 00:30:33,884
[SPEAKER_01]: Not to do it in July and August.

458
00:30:34,064 --> 00:30:34,204
[SPEAKER_02]: No.

459
00:30:35,885 --> 00:30:36,566
[SPEAKER_01]: We learned the hard way.

460
00:30:36,746 --> 00:30:39,308
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, July and August, not much goes on.

461
00:30:40,229 --> 00:30:44,373
[SPEAKER_02]: A lot of people, vacation time, put it that way.

462
00:30:44,393 --> 00:30:47,436
[SPEAKER_02]: A lot of us learned that the hard way in July and August.

463
00:30:48,276 --> 00:30:52,140
[SPEAKER_02]: Alright, so you're brought up about the books and everything else.

464
00:30:52,200 --> 00:30:54,102
[SPEAKER_02]: Are you planning, you know,

465
00:30:55,855 --> 00:30:57,775
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's get into what you got planned.

466
00:30:57,795 --> 00:30:59,776
[SPEAKER_02]: You got anything planned?

467
00:30:59,936 --> 00:31:05,817
[SPEAKER_02]: You inviting someone to these book events?

468
00:31:05,957 --> 00:31:08,557
[SPEAKER_02]: Or anyone you're excited to bring to Method?

469
00:31:08,997 --> 00:31:10,298
[SPEAKER_01]: Our last one was two weeks ago.

470
00:31:11,318 --> 00:31:17,019
[SPEAKER_01]: We won't do another one until the fall, but in the fall, we'll probably have three or four in September and October.

471
00:31:17,779 --> 00:31:19,459
[SPEAKER_01]: And they'll all be people who've done new books.

472
00:31:20,239 --> 00:31:23,920
[SPEAKER_01]: We had a wonderful book signing, our last Saturday one, that was somewhat of a success.

473
00:31:24,981 --> 00:31:28,746
[SPEAKER_01]: A woman who went to MassArt, I think, 30 years ago.

474
00:31:28,846 --> 00:31:33,393
[SPEAKER_01]: She's done five books about the Basque country, you know, the Spanish part of Spain.

475
00:31:34,314 --> 00:31:35,876
[SPEAKER_01]: She's a great photographer.

476
00:31:36,697 --> 00:31:40,082
[SPEAKER_01]: And back in the 70s, I was a fan of punk rock.

477
00:31:41,086 --> 00:31:43,827
[SPEAKER_01]: And I liked Willie Loco Alexander.

478
00:31:44,567 --> 00:31:46,867
[SPEAKER_01]: And I like Lou Reed and Velvet Underground.

479
00:31:46,887 --> 00:31:48,448
[SPEAKER_02]: Lou Reed and the Velvet Underground.

480
00:31:48,468 --> 00:31:49,528
[SPEAKER_02]: Wow, what memories.

481
00:31:50,188 --> 00:31:52,169
[SPEAKER_01]: She lives in Gloucester for the last 40 years.

482
00:31:52,209 --> 00:31:57,150
[SPEAKER_01]: She comes to the opening with a bunch of her very rare books, which we sold a bunch for her.

483
00:31:57,190 --> 00:32:01,531
[SPEAKER_01]: And her husband of 40 years is Willie Loco Alexander.

484
00:32:01,571 --> 00:32:02,251
[SPEAKER_01]: No kidding.

485
00:32:02,431 --> 00:32:04,872
[SPEAKER_01]: Who replaced Lou Reed at the Velvet Underground.

486
00:32:05,872 --> 00:32:07,794
[SPEAKER_01]: with his hair still spiked up.

487
00:32:07,854 --> 00:32:09,416
[SPEAKER_01]: He's six foot eight.

488
00:32:10,618 --> 00:32:11,799
[SPEAKER_01]: And he's funny as hell.

489
00:32:11,899 --> 00:32:12,760
[SPEAKER_01]: And he was a painter.

490
00:32:13,421 --> 00:32:21,170
[SPEAKER_01]: And everyone that didn't know them was so surprised that Willie Loco, he's a foot taller than she is.

491
00:32:21,190 --> 00:32:22,531
[SPEAKER_01]: And he paints wonderfully.

492
00:32:23,993 --> 00:32:33,203
[SPEAKER_01]: But it's like whoever would have thought that I would get to meet Willy Loco Alexander, and that his wife would be an artist who I respect incredibly.

493
00:32:33,383 --> 00:32:34,104
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a great thing.

494
00:32:34,204 --> 00:32:36,226
[SPEAKER_01]: That's Ann Rierich, by the way.

495
00:32:36,306 --> 00:32:38,688
[SPEAKER_00]: She's incredibly talented, incredibly kind.

496
00:32:39,049 --> 00:32:40,750
[SPEAKER_00]: You meet her and you feel like you've known her for 20 years.

497
00:32:41,431 --> 00:32:42,592
[SPEAKER_01]: And she teaches kids.

498
00:32:43,552 --> 00:32:46,593
[SPEAKER_01]: She teaches at the high school level.

499
00:32:46,974 --> 00:32:53,156
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's rare that you have someone of that caliber who shows and photographs her in major collections.

500
00:32:53,256 --> 00:32:54,797
[SPEAKER_02]: That's teaching at that level.

501
00:32:55,317 --> 00:32:55,998
[SPEAKER_02]: That's a good thing.

502
00:32:56,738 --> 00:32:58,439
[SPEAKER_01]: So that was a great benefit.

503
00:32:59,059 --> 00:32:59,559
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm sure.

504
00:32:59,799 --> 00:33:00,680
[SPEAKER_02]: I like that story.

505
00:33:02,920 --> 00:33:03,821
[SPEAKER_02]: That's a classic.

506
00:33:04,661 --> 00:33:05,461
[SPEAKER_02]: That's a classic.

507
00:33:05,662 --> 00:33:14,046
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, Ross and I talk about sometimes people that we think are, you know, well, we'll work with them.

508
00:33:14,106 --> 00:33:15,027
[SPEAKER_01]: They're so exciting.

509
00:33:15,327 --> 00:33:15,567
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

510
00:33:15,747 --> 00:33:21,951
[SPEAKER_01]: And sometimes there are people that we work with that afterwards you say, God, I hope we don't have to do that again.

511
00:33:22,971 --> 00:33:23,852
[SPEAKER_02]: We all go through it.

512
00:33:26,253 --> 00:33:27,614
[SPEAKER_02]: This is going to be the last question.

513
00:33:28,174 --> 00:33:30,776
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm only asking this out of my own curiosity.

514
00:33:33,065 --> 00:33:38,285
[SPEAKER_02]: I gotta ask you, alright, I know your worlds collided, whatever, but how did you guys meet?

515
00:33:39,178 --> 00:33:40,079
[SPEAKER_00]: Let me take this one.

516
00:33:40,719 --> 00:33:48,323
[SPEAKER_00]: When I was in school, Arlette's gallery, Gallery Kefes, was, as Gus mentioned, the best photography gallery in Boston.

517
00:33:49,284 --> 00:33:59,050
[SPEAKER_00]: I went to openings there to see contemporary work and a friend of mine when I was at school became Arlette's assistant.

518
00:34:00,311 --> 00:34:03,292
[SPEAKER_00]: I was envious because I wanted to be connected with that gallery.

519
00:34:05,438 --> 00:34:11,041
[SPEAKER_00]: He eventually reached out to me because he said, hey, Arlette's husband needs some help with some framing jobs.

520
00:34:11,381 --> 00:34:13,262
[SPEAKER_00]: And I had been working at a frame shop.

521
00:34:14,123 --> 00:34:16,104
[SPEAKER_00]: I didn't know who Gus was at the time.

522
00:34:16,384 --> 00:34:19,926
[SPEAKER_00]: And I said, sure, if it's at the gallery, I'm happy to get involved.

523
00:34:20,607 --> 00:34:26,630
[SPEAKER_00]: I got there and immediately we left the gallery and went to the place in Chelsea, which I was like, where the hell is this guy taking me?

524
00:34:28,302 --> 00:34:31,106
[SPEAKER_00]: When I get there, I recognize there's a massive darkroom in here.

525
00:34:31,146 --> 00:34:32,948
[SPEAKER_00]: And I didn't have access to a darkroom at the time.

526
00:34:32,968 --> 00:34:35,992
[SPEAKER_00]: I had finished school and I was looking for access to a darkroom.

527
00:34:36,172 --> 00:34:38,836
[SPEAKER_00]: So I helped him with a couple of frame jobs.

528
00:34:39,136 --> 00:34:44,623
[SPEAKER_00]: I was working for him maybe once a week and started trading access to the darkroom.

529
00:34:46,145 --> 00:34:49,167
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, and then started working on some printing jobs for Gus.

530
00:34:49,828 --> 00:34:58,615
[SPEAKER_00]: And, you know, it eventually became clear that we had a similar sensibility as to what looks great and, you know, how to do it and how to produce it efficiently.

531
00:34:59,898 --> 00:35:02,682
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, you know, Gus is a well-known photographer.

532
00:35:02,702 --> 00:35:05,966
[SPEAKER_00]: He has worked in many, many museums.

533
00:35:06,527 --> 00:35:11,674
[SPEAKER_00]: It wasn't until after I started working for him that I really started to understand who he was.

534
00:35:11,794 --> 00:35:15,880
[SPEAKER_00]: And occasionally we've started to work on some of Gus's

535
00:35:16,580 --> 00:35:17,321
[SPEAKER_01]: That was always fun.

536
00:35:17,401 --> 00:35:22,564
[SPEAKER_00]: Gus has a lifetime of photographs that have either not been printed or haven't been looked at in years.

537
00:35:22,644 --> 00:35:31,510
[SPEAKER_00]: And part of the future of Palm Press, as I hope to take it over, is we'll be printing some- I'll be a client instead of- There you go.

538
00:35:31,550 --> 00:35:32,771
[SPEAKER_00]: Printing some of Gus's work.

539
00:35:33,172 --> 00:35:34,913
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's how it came to be.

540
00:35:35,013 --> 00:35:36,494
[SPEAKER_00]: And yeah, we'll see.

541
00:35:36,574 --> 00:35:37,314
[SPEAKER_00]: We'll see where it goes.

542
00:35:37,975 --> 00:35:44,759
[SPEAKER_01]: One of the things I discovered that when you bring someone on board, usually there's a lot that they have to unlearn.

543
00:35:45,740 --> 00:35:47,141
[SPEAKER_01]: bad habits.

544
00:35:47,701 --> 00:35:50,683
[SPEAKER_01]: Ross, there was very, very little that Ross had to unlearn.

545
00:35:50,723 --> 00:35:52,143
[SPEAKER_01]: And he is such an eager student.

546
00:35:52,904 --> 00:35:54,385
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, is there a way we can do this?

547
00:35:54,445 --> 00:35:56,546
[SPEAKER_01]: And I would remember some obscure chemist.

548
00:35:57,426 --> 00:35:59,547
[SPEAKER_01]: And he would incorporate it into what he did.

549
00:35:59,607 --> 00:36:07,071
[SPEAKER_01]: And he's come up with technical solutions for some of our clients' work, which you would think would be impossible.

550
00:36:07,192 --> 00:36:11,574
[SPEAKER_01]: And they're brilliant, like the large digital negatives you made for the Iowa person.

551
00:36:12,755 --> 00:36:14,075
[SPEAKER_00]: So one of the things that we've done is

552
00:36:15,636 --> 00:36:24,418
[SPEAKER_00]: figured out a way to take a digital image, even sometimes iPhone images, and produce a negative by printing it on our inkjet printer.

553
00:36:24,718 --> 00:36:27,999
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we use that negative to print it as a silver print in the darkroom.

554
00:36:28,139 --> 00:36:28,819
[SPEAKER_00]: And they're beautiful.

555
00:36:28,879 --> 00:36:31,240
[SPEAKER_00]: They're more beautiful than we thought they possibly could be.

556
00:36:32,300 --> 00:36:33,220
[SPEAKER_02]: That's a great story.

557
00:36:33,840 --> 00:36:35,681
[SPEAKER_02]: But I'm sorry, you know, we got to end the show now.

558
00:36:35,941 --> 00:36:37,601
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't want to end it.

559
00:36:37,641 --> 00:36:38,061
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't.

560
00:36:38,081 --> 00:36:41,202
[SPEAKER_02]: But, you know, time constraints, you know.

561
00:36:41,782 --> 00:36:43,944
[SPEAKER_02]: But I wanna, I really thank you both.

562
00:36:45,965 --> 00:36:47,947
[SPEAKER_02]: It's that time again, we have to end it.

563
00:36:48,887 --> 00:36:54,031
[SPEAKER_02]: I wanna thank Ross and Gus for joining us on Method Happenings.

564
00:36:54,651 --> 00:36:59,915
[SPEAKER_02]: And I wish, we really do wish continued success at Palm Press Studio.

565
00:37:00,636 --> 00:37:04,458
[SPEAKER_02]: I also wanna take a minute, thank everyone who has been watching the show.

566
00:37:04,999 --> 00:37:06,360
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you for your feedback.

567
00:37:07,120 --> 00:37:09,042
